CTD χpod A05 section¶

https://cchdo.ucsd.edu/cruise/74EQ20151206

  1. [ ] convert datetime properly

  2. [ ] Plot spiciness to decide how to cut up section into segments

  3. [ ] write function to process segments

  4. [ ] make sure data is thorpesorted before attempting estimate

  5. [ ] NATRE has KtTz < 0 in some places. avg does not.

Suggestions¶

  1. Don’t set lat, lon=0 when data is missing

  2. lat, lon should match the CTD data exactly

  3. Need cast numbers that line up with CTD file

  4. cast 131 looks bad

  5. Put EXPOCODE in final file to be clear about which cruise

    Looking at χ distributions: A05 vs NATRE¶

    Why is the error so big around 1000m

    1. Error is sensitive to blocksize; I think this is wrong for large blocksize, we don’t get enough independent samples.

    2. NATRE has 5x more points (after coarsening to 2m) but masking out a few high values really reduces error in A05

      1. The high value criterion depends on depth (by comparing with NATRE)

        1. at 1300-ish m we need to throw out χ > 1e-7 (approx.)

        2. at 900-ish m we need to throw out χ > 1e-6 (approx).

    from eddydiff.sections import compute_bootstrapped_mean_ci

inds = slice(4, 14)
print(f"depth range: {np.arange(150, 3150, 100)[inds]}")
print(f"density bins: {bins[inds]}")

print(bins[inds])
grouped = subset.groupby_bins("gamma_n", bins=bins[inds])
print(bins[inds])
natre_grouped = natre.groupby_bins("gamma_n", bins=bins[inds])

binsize = 20


for label, group in grouped:
    print(label)
    group.attrs["name"] = "A05"
    natre_group = natre_grouped[label]
    natre_group.attrs["name"] = "NATRE"

    f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, sharey=True, constrained_layout=True)

    for group_, yerr in zip((group, natre_group), [0.5, 0.6]):
        mask = (group_.chi < 1e-7) & (group_.eps < 1e-7)
        group_ = group_.pint.quantify().pint.dequantify()

        for varname, axx in zip(["chi", "eps"], ax):

            kwargs = dict(ax=axx, density=True, histtype="step", lw=1.5)

            var = group_[varname]
            npts = var.notnull().sum().item()
            err = compute_bootstrapped_mean_ci(var.to_numpy(), binsize)
            _, histbins, hdl = np.log10(var.as_numpy()).plot.hist(
                bins=101, label=f"{group_.attrs['name']}, {npts} pts", **kwargs
            )

            var = group_[varname].where(mask)
            npts = var.notnull().sum().item()
            mask_err = compute_bootstrapped_mean_ci(var.where(mask).to_numpy(), binsize)
            _, _, hdl1 = np.log10(var.as_numpy()).plot.hist(
                bins=histbins,
                label=f"{group_.attrs['name']}, masked,  {npts} pts",
                **kwargs,
            )

            ecolors = (hdl[0].get_edgecolor(), hdl1[0].get_edgecolor())
            for e, dy, c in zip([err, mask_err], [-0.01, +0.01], ecolors):
                axx.plot(np.log10(e), np.ones((3,)) * (yerr + dy), color=c, marker=".")
            axx.set_xticks(np.arange(-13, -5, 1))
            axx.set_title("")
    axx.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    f.suptitle(
        f"$γ_n$ bin = {label} | depth bin = {group.pressure.mean().item():.2f}, {natre_group.pres.mean().item():.2f}"
    )
    f.set_size_inches((8, 3))

    Using \(K_ρ (T_z^m)^2\)¶

    Note this doesn’t work so well. But is entirely consistent with an equivalent effort using \(⟨ε_χ⟩\) estimated from the NATRE experiment.

plt.xscale("log")

    Comparing some terms¶

    f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, sharey=True, constrained_layout=True)

for var, axx in zip(["chi", "hm", "residual"], ax.flat):
    dcpy.plots.fill_between_bounds(avg, var, y="pres", ax=axx)
    dcpy.plots.fill_between_bounds(natre_binned, var, y="pres", color="k", ax=axx)
    axx.set_ylim((2000, 200))
    axx.set_xlabel(var)
ax[0].set_xscale("log")
ax[2].set_xscale("log")

plt.gcf().set_size_inches((4, 6))

    avg.gamma_n.plot(y="pres", marker="x")
